US-listed Chinese companies traded lower on Thursday with nine of the top 10 stocks by weight in the S&P US Listed China 50 index ending the day on a downbeat note. Shares of New Oriental Education & Technology Group and Yum China Holdings declined nearly 3 percent and over 2.7 percent respectively, leading the losers in the top 10 stocks of the index. Shares of JD.com, bucking the trend, rose more than 2.3 percent, the only gainer in the top 10 stocks of the index. US stocks closed lower on Thursday, as investors continued to watch closely the development regarding global trade. The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 138.97 points, or 0.54 percent, to 25,828.36. The S&P 500 decreased 8.70 points, or 0.30 percent, to 2,870.72. The Nasdaq Composite Index fell 32.73 points, or 0.41 percent, to 7,910.59. The Cboe Volatility index, widely considered the best fear gauge in the stock market, decreased 1.55 percent to 19.1 on Thursday. As of Wednesday, the S&P US Listed China 50 index stood at 2,846.71, marking a 5.60-percent decrease for the month-to-date returns and a 24.24-percent gain for the year-to-date returns. Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Actress Liu honored with Hollywood Walk of Fame starDelegation of HUST attends alumni gala in Los AngelesChinese driving Vegas growth